title: SpaceX preparing to start Starlink Gen2 launches this month
summary: SpaceX could start launching second-generation Starlink satellites in the coming weeks to add more capacity to its increasingly congested broadband network.

title: NASA to Air Live Coverage of US Spacewalk for Solar Array Installation
summary: NASA astronauts aboard the International Space Station will conduct a spacewalk on Wednesday, Dec. 21, to install a rollout solar array to increase electrical power in support of operations and scientific research.

title: With Hubble and Spitzer, researchers discover water-filled exoplanets
summary: Using data from NASA’s Hubble Space Telescope and retired Spitzer Space Telescope, a group of researchers has discovered two exoplanets that may be largely comprised of water. Located around a red dwarf star 218 light-years away, the two planets are low in density.

title: Russia says it will take no immediate action on damaged Soyuz spacecraft
summary: In reality, the Soyuz is a hardy spacecraft.

title: South Korean spacecraft enters lunar orbit with deceleration maneuver
summary: South Korea’s first robotic lunar orbiter, Danuri, entered the lunar orbit after conducting its first lunar orbit insertion maneuver Dec. 16.

title: SpaceX aces three Falcon 9 launches in 34 hours
summary: SpaceX has successfully launched three Falcon 9 rockets less than 34 hours apart, leaving the company only one mission shy of CEO...

title: Weather and range issues delay first Electron launch from Wallops to January
summary: Rocket Lab will have to wait until January for its next attempt at its inaugural Electron launch from Virginia after suffering delays because of weather and range issues.

title: L3Harris to acquire Aerojet Rocketdyne for $4.7 billion
summary: L3Harris Technologies on Dec. 18 announced an agreement to acquire Aerojet Rocketdyne for $4.7 billion.

title: NASA signs spaceflight safety agreement with AST SpaceMobile
summary: NASA has signed an agreement with AST SpaceMobile to cooperate on spaceflight safety, even as astronomers grow increasingly concerned about the effects of that company’s satellites.

title: Upper level winds scrub first Electron launch from American soil
summary: Rocket Lab, which has operated its Electron small-satellite launcher successfully from New Zealand since 2017, is about to inaugurate its first US-based launch site. After weather and paperwork-related delays, the mission named “Virginia Is For Launch Lovers” was set to lift off within a two-hour window beginning at 6:00 PM EST (23:00 UTC) on Sunday, Dec. 18.
